eng: an Sinus be Cured? “Sinus I nfections Signs and Symptoms”  Sinusitis is an inflammation of the membrane lining of any sinus, especially one of the paranasal sinuses. Actite sinusitis is 2 short-term condition that responds well to antibiotics and decongestants; chronic sinusits is characterized by at least four recurrences of acute sinusitis. Either medication or surgery s a possible treatment.  For acute sinusitis, symptoms include facial pain/pressure, nasal obstruction, nasal discharge, diminished sense of smell, and cough not due to asthma (in children). Additionally, sufferers of this disorder could incur fever, bad breath, fatigue, dental pain, and cough.  Acute sinusitis can last four weeks or more. This condition may be present when the patient has two or more symptoms and/or the presence of thick, green or yellow nasal discharge. Actite bacterial infection might be present when symptoms worsen after five days, persist after ten days, or the severity of symptoms is out of proportion to those normally associated with a viral infection.  Acute sinusi     is generally treated with ten to 14 days of antibiotic care. With treatment, the symptoms disappear, and antibiotics are no longer required for that episode. However, the sinusitis will probably return, and the antibiotics will have weakened your immune system. Oral and topical decongestants also may be prescribed to alleviate the symptoms. These too will have a negative effect on your immune system.  Victims of chronic sinusitis may have the following symptoms for 12 weeks or more: facial pain/pressure, facial congestion/fullness, nasal obstruction /blockage, thick nasal discharge/discolored post-nasal drainage, pus in the nasal cavity, and at times, fever. They may also have headache, bad breath, and fatigue.  Warm moist     ir may alleviate sinus congestion. Experts recommend a vaporizer or steam from a pan of boiled water (removed from the heat). Humidifiers should be used only when a clean filter is in place to preclude spraying bacteria or fungal spores into the air. Warm compresses are useful in relieving pain in the nose and sinuses. Saline nose drops are also helpful in moisturizing nasal passages. The latest sinus infection discovery is now also widely available.

eng: HOME REMEDIES —T0 TREAT—     WHAT IS WHEEZING?  ‘Wheezing is when you are unable to breathe properly. Air is passing into the lungs and is being exhaled as well, but the process is not smooth and efficient. Wheezing happens when there is a blockage that impedes the flow of air in and out of the lungs.  Garlic is very useful in treating breathing difficulties and removing the wheezing sound. It has amazing anti-oxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. Its antibiotic action takes care of the viral infection, reducing the inflammation and clearing the congestion in the lungs.     Ginger is a popular natural treatment for various illnesses including asthma. It is known to reduce respiratory tract inflammation and inhibit its contraction.     The nutritive properties of figs encourage respiratory health and help remove phlegm and reduce breathing difficulties.  ‘Wash three dried figs and soak them in a cup of water overnight. In the morning, eat the soaked figs and drink the fig water on an empty stomach.     Try and eat raw onions with all your meals. The sulfur present in compounds found in onions contains antimicrobial elements that combat all kinds of infections. Onions are helpful against wheezing, and also against colds and coughs.     CLICK TO READ MORE

Drug classes for allergy treatment  1R  Naphazoline Tetrahydrozoline Phenylephrine Ephedrine Brimonidine  Ketorolac Flurbiprofen Indomethacin Diclofenac Nevanac  Antazoline Pheniramine Levocabastine Emedastine  Cromolyn Nedocromil sodium Pemirolast Lodoxamide  Ketotifen Azelastine Epinastine Bepostatine Olopatadine Alcaftadine  Clobeta-sonebutyrate Dexamethasone Fluoromethalone Hydrocortisone Prednisolone Rimexalone Triamcinolone Lotoprednol  Cyclosporine A     MECHANISM (I HID]  Alpha-adrenergic agonists (mainly alpha-1 receptors)  Inhibition of COX-1 and COX-2 resulting in inhibition of prostaglandins  Competitive blockage of histamine receptors (all block H1, and some block H2, H3, and/or H4)  Inhibition of mast cell degranulation and release of histamine  Blockage of H1 receptors and inhibits mast cell degranulation and histamine release  Inhibition of phospholipase A resulting in inhibition of prostaglandins and leukotriene synthesis  Inhibition of T-cell activation     UL L[ R3320  Rebound hyperemia, conjunctivitis medicamentosa, follicular reaction, contraindicated in narrow angle glaucoma  Burning sensation, itching, corneal melt  Sedation, irritation, dry eye  Headache, burning sensation  Headache, hyperemia, burning sensation, bitter taste, dry eye  Increased intraocular pressure, cataract formation, delayed wound healing, headache, pharyngitis, rhinitis  Irritation, burning sensation        COMMENT  Available alone for ocular redness or in conjunction with first-generation antihistamine in over-the-counter preparations; only last 2 to 4 hours; brimonidine is only alpha-2 agonist soon to be filed with FDA for redness approval only  Approved only for postoperative inflammation; not shown to be effective in many failed clinical trials in perennial allergic conjunctivitis (PAC) and seasonal allergic conjunctivitis (SAC)  The first two are in over-the-counter preparations with vasoconstrictors; levocabastine only available in Europe; emadastine not promoted in United States  This class taken over by dual-acting drugs  Discovery of mast cell heterogeneity abdicated relevance of most of these in the eye; Cromolyn proven not active in human conjunctival mast cells; very weak activity; lodoxamide perhaps most effective in vernal keratoconjunctivitis (VKC)  Most are approved for twice-daily dosing;  CAC trials are gold standard for their approval and comparative testing;  Olopatadine and alcaftadine approved for once daily dosing  Alcaftadine shown to be superior for ocular itching by numerous parameters  Must be used with extreme caution; only for pulse therapy in chronic forms of allergy (VKC, atopic keratoconjunctivitis, etc.)  Only approved for use in dry eye; off-label testing for chronic forms of allergy like VKC

eng: Drug Facts  Active ingredient (in each tablet) Purpose Cetirizine HCI 10 mg.... Antihistamine     Uses temporarily relieves these symptoms due to hay fever or other upper respiratory allergies: mrunnynose Msneezing M itchy, watery eyes M itching of the nose or throat  Warnings Do not use if you have ever had an allergic reaction to this product or any of its ingredients or to an antihistamine containing hydroxyzine.  Ask a doctor before use if you have liver or kidney disease. Your doctor should determine if you need a different dose. Ask a doctor or pharmacist before use if you are taking tranquilizers or sedatives.  When using this product  m drowsiness may occur M avoid alcoholic drinks  m alcohol, sedatives, and tranquilizers may increase drowsiness W be careful when driving a motor vehicle or operating machinery  Stop use and ask a doctor if an allergic reaction to this product occurs. Seek medical help right away. If pregnant or breast-feeding:                 m if breast-feeding: not recommended M if pregnant: ask a health professional before use. Keep out of reach of children. In case of overdose, get medical help or contact a Poison Control Center right away. (1-800-222-1222)  Directions  adults and children one 10 mg tablet once daily; do not take more than one 10 mg tablet in 6 years and over 24 hours. A 5 mg product may be appropriate for less severe symptoms.  adults 65 years and over ask a doctor children under 6 years of age ask a doctor  consumers with liver ask a doctor or kidney disease                 Other information m store between 20-25°C (68-77°F)  Inactive ingredients corn starch, FD&C blue no. 1 aluminum lake, hypromellose, lactose monohydrate, magnesium stearate, polydextrose, polyethylene glycol, povidone, titanium dioxide, triacetin  Questions or comments?1-800-719-9260

eng: Overcoming  SEASONAL AM,ERGMES  EIIE:1]Y  FOODS TO AVOID  Alcohol Artificial sweeteners Shellfish  Caffeine Processed foods Bottled citrus juice Conventional dairy Melons Echinacea Chocolate Bananas Chamonmile Peanuts Cucumbers Wheat  Sugar Sunflower seeds 1l  FOODS TO ENJOY  RAW LOCAL HONEY  Relieves symptoms because it contains local pollen that is causing your allergies. Take a couple of tablespoons each day.  HOT AND SPICY FOODS  Thins the mucus, and allow it to be more easily expressed. Try adding garlic, onion, ginger, cinnamon and cayenne pepper to your recipes.  BONE BROTH  Bone broth, from chicken, beef or lamb, helps to ease respiratory problems, and help to expel excess nasal mucus.  PROBIOTIC-RICH FOODS  Support a stronger immune system, improve digestion, increase energy levels, and so much more. Eat kefir, sauerkraut or kimchi, kombucha, natto, yogurt and raw cheese.  PINEAPPLE  The enzyme Bromelain found in pineapple in addition to high levels of vitamins B, C and other essential nutrients can help to reduce your reaction to seasonal allergies.  APPLE CIDER VINEGAR  Helps to boost the immune system, helps to break up mucus and supports lymphatic drainage. Three times per day, mix 1 tablespoon of ACV with  1 tablespoon of fresh-squeezed lemon juice, and % tablespoon of local raw honey and drink.  FRESH ORGANIC VEGETABLES Include Swiss chard (that is high in quercetin), cabbage, beets, carrots and yams to help you fight seasonal allergies.  CLEAN PROTEINS  Consume grass-fed meats, free-range poultry and wild-caught fish to provide the right vitamins, omega-3s, essential minerals and protein to boost your immunity.  plements to Help e Allergy Fight  Spirulina - 1 teaspoon per day  Stops the release of histamine that causes symptoms.  Quercetin - 1000 mg per day  The flavonoid that gives fruits and vegetables their rich color, quercetin stops the production and release of histamine.  Butterbur - 500 mg per day Traditionally used to treat bronchitis, excess mucus and asthma, it was found to be as effective as Zyrtec/Allegra for  treating hay fever. (However, young children, pregnant or breastfeeding women should not take butterbur supplements.)  Probiotics - 50 billion IU (2-6 capsules) per day Modifies the intestinal flora in the gut improving immune  system and shows promise in the treatment and prevention of allergies.  Vitamin A - 2000 mcg per day  Boosts the immune system, fights inflammation and has antihistamine properties.  Bromelain - 1,000 mg per day  The enzyme in pineapple helps to reduce swelling in the nose and sinuses, helping to relieve hay fever symptoms.  Zinc - 30 mg per day  Helps to heal adrenal fatigue caused by chronic stress, as stress worsens the symptoms of seasonal allergies.  Stinging Nettle - 300-500 mg twice per day  o e e R R T T ey ety help to reduce the body’s production of symptom causing histamine.     Dr. Axe  R

eng: Family Allergy  Asthma, immuno!ogy& nus Center Maryam Zarei, M.D. F.A.ALAAL  Cough-Variant Asthma (CVA)  While cough may accompany the usual symptoms associated with asthma, in CVA, cough alone may be a precursor to or the sole symptom. When cough is the only symptom, this is known as cough variant  asthma (CVA). What is Cough Variant Asthma?  The main symptom of CVA is a chronic, non-productive cough. These asthma patients have cough as the main or only symptom of their asthma. These patients are a small percentage of total asthma patients. CVA patients are, however, a distinct group rather than merely being thought of as 'coughing asthmatics.'  CVA patients have some differences from patients with typical asthma. For example, while normal asthmatics do not differ from healthy volunteers in their cough relex, CVA patients have a more sensitive  cough reflex.  How Is Cough Variant Asthma Diagnosed?  Cough-variant asthma is somewhat difficult to diagnose because the cough may be the only symptom, and the cough itself may appear to be bronchitis or a cough associated with postnasal drip. Your doctor will ask you questions about your medical history and will examine you and listen to you breathe. However, people with CVA often have normal physical examinations, chest X- raL peak flow  measurements and splrometry     Spirometry involves measuring how much air you can exhale after first taking a deep breath, and how quickly you can empty your lungs. A final test may be a Methacholine challenge test to evaluate for asthma, but it may require the use of a special facility. This test may be performed if your symptoms and spirometry test do not clearly show asthma. Interestingly, CVA patients have a smaller reaction to methacholine challenge testing compared to other asthmatics.  How Is Cough Variant Asthma Treated? 3  Treatment of CVA is virtually the same as for asthma. Partial improvement of Chronic cough may be  seen as quickly as 1 week with bronchodilators like Albuterol, but may not completely resolve for up to 8 weeks after starting an inhaled steroid like Flovent.  If the cough only partially resolves, your provider may try a more potent steroid like oral prednisone. Alternatively, your provider may do special tests to identif) eosinophils or feno, a marker of inflammation, in your lung. If eosinophils are present in the lung, Other medications like singulair may be beneficial.  A small group of patients may experience worsening of the cough with inhaled steroids due to the aersols used in the inhaler device. Alternatively, if the cough worsens, it is important to rule out other conditions like allergies, or Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD).  Office: 15725 Pomerado Road, Suite # 103, Poway Ca 92064 / Tel. (858) 521-0806 Fax (858) 521-0808

Interestingly, CVA patients have a smaller reaction to methacholine challenge testing compared to other asthmatics.  How Is Cough Variant Asthma Treated? !  |Treatment of CVA is virtually the same as for asthma. Partial improvement of Chronic cough may be  seen as quickly as 1 week with bronchodilators like Albuterol, but may not completely resolve for up to 8 weeks after starting an inhaled steroid like Flovent.  If the cough only partially resolves, your provider may try a more potent steroid like oral prednisone. Alternatively, your provider may do special tests to identify eosinophils or feno, a marker of inflammation, in your lung. If eosinophils are present in the lung, Other medications like singulair may be beneficial.  A small group of patients may experience worsening of the cough with inhaled steroids due to the aersols used in the inhaler device. Alternatively, ¡f the cough worsens, it is important to rule out other conditions like allergies, or Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD). Cough-Variant Asthma (CVA)  While cough may accompany the usual symptoms associated with asthma, in CVA, cough alone may be a precursor to or the sole symptom. When cough is the only symptom, this is known as cough variant  asthma (CVA). What is Cough Variant Asthma2  The main symptom ofCVA is a chronic, non-productive cough. These asthma patients have cough as the maln or only symptom of their asthma. These patients are a small percentage of total asthma patients:. CVA patients are, however, a distinct group rather than merely being thought ofas coughing asthmatics.  CVA patients have some differences from patients with typical asthma. For example, while normal asthmatics do not differ from healthy volunteers in their cough relex, CVA patients have a more sensitive  COugh reflex.  How Is Cough Variant Asthma Diagnosed2  Cough-variant asthma is somewhat difficult to diagnose because the cough may be the only symptom, and the cough itself may appear to be bronchitis or a cough associated with postnasal drip. Your doctor will ask you questions about your medical history and will examine you and listen to you breathe. However, people with CVA often have normal physical examinations, chest X- ra义′ peak flow  Imeasurements and spirometry.     Spirometry involyes measuring how much air you can exhale after first taking a deep breath, and how quickly you can empty your Iungs.
